## Create your first Docker image (real hands‑on example)

    We’ll build a simple web server using a Docker image 
    This is the easiest and clearest way to understand:
        • Dockerfile
        • Layers
        • Build context
        • Image creation
        • Running your custom image
    Let’s begin.

    Step 1: Create a project folder on your machine

                mkdir mydockerapp
                cd mydockerapp 
            
            Inside this folder, Create a file 
                echo "Hello from my first Docker image!" > index.html

            This will be the content served by your container.

    Step 2: Create your first Dockerfile

            Inside the same folder, create a file named:
                Dockerfile 

            Put this inside it: 
                
                FROM nginx:alpine
                COPY index.html /usr/share/nginx/html/index.html

            What this Dockerfile means:
                • FROM nginx:alpine
                You are using the official Nginx image as the base.

                • COPY index.html …
                You are replacing the default Nginx homepage with your own.

                This is the simplest possible real‑world Docker image.

    Step 3: Build the image 

                docker build -t myweb:v1 .
            
            Breakdown:
                • -t myweb:v1 → name and version of your image
                • . → build context (current folder): he . means “take everything in the current folder and send it to Docker as the build context.”

            Docker will show:
                • Step 1/2 FROM nginx:alpine
                • Step 2/2 COPY index.html …
                • Successfully built
            This means your image is ready.

    Step 4: Run your custom image 
            
            docker run -p 8080:80 myweb:v1

            Now open: http://localhost:8080

    Step 5: Why the build context matters?

            When you run: 
                docker build -t myweb:v1 .

            Docker does not just read the Dockerfile.
            It sends all files in the folder (your build context) to the Docker Engine.
            Then the Dockerfile can use those files with instructions like:
                • COPY
                • ADD
            This is why the . is important.     

           # ** If your folder has 1 GB of files, Docker will send all 1 GB to the build engine — even if you only copy one file.
            This is why .dockerignore exists. 

    
    Step 6: Lets modify this image to understand layers. 

        Now we’ll add a second file and rebuild the image so you can see how Docker layers work.

        step 6.1: Add another file
                In your project folder

                echo "This is version 2" > version.txt

        Step 6.2 — Update your Dockerfile

                Add this line: 

                FROM nginx:alpine
                COPY index.html /usr/share/nginx/html/index.html
                COPY version.txt /usr/share/nginx/html/version.txt
        
        step 6.3: Build again 

                docker build -t myweb:v2 .

            Docker will show something interesting:
                • Step 1 (FROM) → cached
                • Step 2 (COPY index.html) → cached
                • Step 3 (COPY version.txt) → new layer
            This is your first real experience with Docker layer caching.

    Step 7: Run version 2
            
            docker run -p 8081:80 myweb:v2

            Open: http://localhost:8081/version.txt
            
            You will see: 
            This is version 2


